#View(esoph)

The dataset esoph is called Smoking, Alcohol and (O)esophageal Cancer, written by Thomas Lumley. There are 5 variables: the Age group (agegp), the Alcohol consumption (alcgp), Tobacco consumption (tobgp), Number of cases (ncases), and Number of controls (ncontrols).

From these, Age group, Alcohol consumption and Tobacco consumption are ordinal variables, meaning that they have continuous ranges as their variables.

For the variable Age group they are:

  • 25-34 years
  • 35-44 years
  • 45-54 years
  • 55-64 years
  • 65-74 years
  • 75+ years

For the variable Alcohol consumption they are:

  • 0-39 gm/day
  • 40-79 gm/day
  • 80-119 gm/day
  • 120+ gm/day

For the variable Tobacco consumption they are:

  • 0-9 gm/day
  • 10-19 gm/day
  • 20-29 gm/day
  • 30+ gm/day

The variables Number of cases and Number of controls are doubles (so numbers) and this allows us to compute their median and mean.

library(tidyverse)
## Loading tidyverse: ggplot2
## Loading tidyverse: tibble
## Loading tidyverse: tidyr
## Loading tidyverse: readr
## Loading tidyverse: purrr

## filter(): dplyr, stats
## lag():    dplyr, stats
esoph %>%
  select(ncases, ncontrols) %>%
  summarise(median(ncases), mean(ncases), 
            median(ncontrols), mean(ncontrols))
##   median(ncases) mean(ncases) median(ncontrols) mean(ncontrols)
## 1              1     2.272727                 6        11.07955

There are on average (mean) 2.272727 cases, but the median is 1.

There are on average (mean) 11.07955 controls, but the median is 6.

  filter(agegp == "25-34" | agegp == "45-54") %>%
  group_by(agegp, alcgp) %>%
  summarise(ncases = sum(ncases), 
            ncontrols = sum(ncontrols))

library(dplyr)

df.bike %>%
  filter(act == 1) %>% #
  select(sna, bemp, sbi, tot) %>%
  mutate( = bemp / tot * 100) %>%
  filter( >= 95) %>%
  arrange(desc()) %>%
  rename("" = sna,
         "" = bemp,
         "" = sbi,
         "" = tot)

This is the preparatory code:

df.map <- df.bike %>%
  filter(act == 1) %>% # 
  mutate(vacancy = bemp / tot * 100) %>%
  select(station = sna,
         lat,
         long = lng,
         adress = ar,
         vacancy)

This is my first map. It is a bit zoomed out so I can get all the stations.

library(ggmap)
my_location <- c(lon=121.55, lat=25.05)

my_map <- get_map(location = my_location,
                 source ="google",
                 maptype = "roadmap",
                 zoom = 12)
## Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=25.05,121.55&zoom=12&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=roadmap&language=en-EN&sensor=false
bikemap1 <- ggmap(my_map) +
  geom_point(data = df.map, 
             mapping = aes(x = long, 
                           y = lat,
                           color = vacancy)) +
  ggtitle("Youbike data: 9 October 2017") +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("")
